          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">What makes bathroom fitting in Liverpool's older homes different?</h3>
          <p>Liverpool's Victorian and Edwardian terraces dominate the city's housing stock. These properties have characteristics that require specialist knowledge: solid external walls with no cavity, waste pipes routing through multiple floors, old cast iron soil stacks, original cornicing and features worth preserving, and limited space in back additions. Our team has 30 years fitting bathrooms in Liverpool's terraced streets and understands how to solve these challenges without compromising the quality of the finished result. The <a href="https://www.ciphe.org.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chartered Institute of Plumbing and Heating Engineering</a> sets the standards we work to on every installation.</p>
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">Do I need planning permission for a bathroom renovation in Liverpool?</h3>
          <p>In most cases no. Standard bathroom renovations do not require planning permission in Liverpool. However, if you are converting a bedroom to an en suite, adding an extension to house a new bathroom or making structural changes, you may need <a href="https://liverpool.gov.uk/planning-and-building-control/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Liverpool City Council planning approval</a>. We advise on all regulatory requirements at the free survey visit.</p>
